It‚Äôs  August 2025, and even now, I still remember her‚Äîmy first love. We started talking in 2022, and over two years, something real grew between us. At least, that‚Äôs what I believed. We shared countless conversations, late-night thoughts, silly jokes, and quiet moments that made me feel like we had something special. On the night of November 19th, I finally opened up and proposed to her online. She didn‚Äôt say yes, but she didn‚Äôt shut the door either. She gave me something both beautiful and painful: hope. She told me maybe we‚Äôd be in a relationship in 2025. I held onto that for so long. That small hope became something I carried through everything‚Äîthe hard days, the lonely nights, the changing years. But today, in August 2025, that hope finally broke. I saw her with someone else. Laughing. Holding hands. Happy. And the worst part? I stood there quietly, watching the girl I once dreamed of building a future with, now living a different story‚Äîone that I‚Äôm not part of. It hurt more than I want to admit. Not because she moved on‚ÄîI know people grow, change, choose different paths‚Äîbut because for so long, I believed that maybe, just maybe, we were still written into each other's futures. She wasn‚Äôt just someone I liked. She was the first person I ever truly loved. That kind of love doesn't fade easily. It lingers, even when it‚Äôs no longer returned. And while I know I have to move forward, I also know it‚Äôs okay to feel the sadness. It‚Äôs okay to miss what could‚Äôve been. But I‚Äôm also learning that love isn‚Äôt just about getting someone in the end‚Äîit‚Äôs about what that person awakened in you. She taught me how deep I could feel, how much I could care, how brave I could be when I‚Äôm vulnerable. Maybe that was her role in my life‚Äînot to stay, but to show me what love looks like, even if it wasn‚Äôt mine to keep. She‚Äôll always be my first love. Not my forever, not my ending‚Äîbut a part of me I‚Äôll always remember with both pain and quiet gratitude.
